  abstract = {Submodular function maximization is a central problem in combinatorial optimization, generalizing many important problems including Max Cut in directed/undirected graphs and in hypergraphs, certain constraint satisfaction problems, maximum entropy sampling, and maximum facility location problems. Unlike submodular minimization, submodular maximization is NP-hard. For the problem of maximizing a non-monotone submodular function, Feige, Mirrokni, and Vondr{\textbackslash}'ak recently developed a \$2{\textbackslash}over 5\$-approximation algorithm {\textbackslash}cite\{FMV07\}, however, their algorithms do not handle side constraints.\vphantom\{\} In this paper, we give the first constant-factor approximation algorithm for maximizing any non-negative submodular function subject to multiple matroid or knapsack constraints. We emphasize that our results are for \{{\textbackslash}em non-monotone\} submodular functions. In particular, for any constant \$k\$, we present a \$(\{1{\textbackslash}over k+2+\{1{\textbackslash}over k\}+{\textbackslash}epsilon\})\$-approximation for the submodular maximization problem under \$k\$ matroid constraints, and a \$(\{1{\textbackslash}over 5\}-{\textbackslash}epsilon)\$-approximation algorithm for this problem subject to \$k\$ knapsack constraints (\${\textbackslash}epsilon{$>$}0\$ is any constant). We improve the approximation guarantee of our algorithm to \$\{1{\textbackslash}over k+1+\{1{\textbackslash}over k-1\}+{\textbackslash}epsilon\}\$ for \$k{\textbackslash}ge 2\$ partition matroid constraints. This idea also gives a \$(\{1{\textbackslash}over k+{\textbackslash}epsilon\})\$-approximation for maximizing a \{{\textbackslash}em monotone\} submodular function subject to \$k{\textbackslash}ge 2\$ partition matroids, which improves over the previously best known guarantee of \${\textbackslash}frac\{1\}\{k+1\}\$.},
